<?xml version="1.0" ?>
<gdml xmlns:gdml="http://cern.ch/2001/Schemas/GDML" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="GDMLSchema/gdml.xsd">
<!-- 

07-Apr-2020 WGS: 

Everything in this file is preliminary. Please assume it's wrong
until you're satisfied that it's right. By the way, I composed the
scintillators of milk chocolate; you'd better look up what 
scintillator is actually made of. Similarly with PTFE, which I assume
was a 50/50 mix of platinum and iron. 

No, not really. But please look at everything in this file as if it were
a potential joke. Do NOT treat it as a black box whose contents cannot
be changed!

Source for all the serious stuff: the GRAMS paper arXiv:1901.03430v3
Source for the mistakes and stupid jokes: William Seligman (WGS) seligman@nevis.columbia.edu

-->

  <define>

    <position name="posCenter" unit="cm" x="0" y="0" z="0"/>

    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: Everything will eventually get placed into a large
    world volume. Typically you want a volume that's big enough to contain 
    everything you're modeling, plus some space to both inject incoming
    particles and track outgong particles from the detector simulation. -->
    
    <quantity name="worldVolumeXSize" type="length" value="250" unit="cm" />
    <quantity name="worldVolumeYSize" type="length" value="400" unit="cm" />
    <quantity name="worldVolumeZSize" type="length" value="500" unit="cm" />
    
    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: All length units are cm. Many of the dimensions
    used below are 'constant' or 'variable' so they can be used in calculations. -->

    <!-- ************** LArTPC section ************** -->
    
    <constant name="lArTPCXSize" value="20" />
    <constant name="lArTPCYSize" value="140" />
    <constant name="lArTPCZSize" value="20" />

    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: For all I know the cryostat will be made of insulating foam.
    With no other information, I'm assuming a steel cryostat of 1cm thickness. -->
    <constant name="cryostatThickness" value="1.0" />
    <constant name="cryostatXSize" value="lArTPCXSize + 2*cryostatThickness" />
    <constant name="cryostatYSize" value="lArTPCYSize + 2*cryostatThickness" />
    <constant name="cryostatZSize" value="lArTPCZSize + 2*cryostatThickness" />

    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: For the x-y wires, use the wire spacing from the paper (0.2mm) 
    and radius from MicroBooNE.-->
    <constant name="wireSpacing" value="0.02" />
    <constant name="wireRadius" value="0.0075" />
    <constant name="lengthXWire" value="lArTPCXSize" />
    <constant name="lengthYWire" value="lArTPCYSize" />
    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: Since I have to pick one plane (X or Y) to be the anode plane,
    I'll pick X. The X-plane defines z=0 for the coordinate system (this is a LArSoft
    convention). The distance between planes comes from MicroBoone: 3mm -->
    <constant name="planeSeparation" value="0.3" />
    
    <!-- 6-May-2020 WGS: Define "wire planes" in which to place the wires. This extra
    layer of geometry will make things easier in the long run; e.g., for placing the wires
    within a mechanical frame. -->
    <constant name="wirePlaneThickness" value="0.15" />
    <constant name="wirePlaneXSize" value="lArTPCXSize" />
    <constant name="wirePlaneYSize" value="lArTPCYSize" />
    <constant name="wirePlaneZSize" value="wirePlaneThickness" />
    
    <!-- 6-May-2020 WGS: Create values and variables for loop statements
    when we place the wires in the planes; see the <structure> section. -->
    <constant name="numberXWires" value="( wirePlaneYSize / wireSpacing ) - 1" />
    <constant name="numberYWires" value="( wirePlaneXSize / wireSpacing ) - 1" />
    
    <variable name="xWireLoopIndex" value="0" />
    <variable name="yWireLoopIndex" value="0" />

    <!-- 6-May-2020 WGS: By default, "tubes" are created along the z-axis. We'll
    need a couple of rotation definitions to get the wires to go along the x and y axes.
    -->
    <!-- For y-wires -->
    <rotation name="rPlus90AboutX" unit="deg" x="90" y="0"  z="0"/>
    <!-- For x-wires -->
    <rotation name="rPlus90AboutY" unit="deg" x="0"  y="90" z="0"/>
 
    <!-- 6-May-2020 WGS: There has to be a cathode plate to provide the field along with
    the anode plane (the x-wires in this draft geometry). -->
    <constant name="cathodeThickness" value="0.1" />
    <constant name="cathodeXSize" value="lArTPCXSize" />
    <constant name="cathodeYSize" value="lArTPCYSize" />
    <constant name="cathodeZSize" value="cathodeThickness" />
   
    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: How thick will the PTFE sheets be? I don't know, so 
    assume 1mm. I assume the sheets will be mounted on the x-sides of the TPC. -->
    <constant name="ptfeThickness" value="0.1" />
    <constant name="ptfeXSize" value="lArTPCXSize" />
    <constant name="ptfeYSize" value="ptfeThickness" />
    <constant name="ptfeZSize" value="lArTPCZSize - 1.0" />
    
    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: How many active regions will there be? I don't know, 
    so assume 5 PTFE sheets dividing the LAr into 6 regions (the number
    in the diagrams in arXiv:1901.03430v3). -->
    
    <constant name="numberPtfeSheets" value="5" />
    <constant name="numberActiveRegions" value="numberPtfeSheets + 1" />

    <!-- 8-May-2020 WGS: How big will the active LAr region be? I don't know. 
    To make the placement of the sensitive detector regions easier, I'm putting a
    2 cm boundary in x and z, but over the complete y-length of the LArTPC. This
    isn't realistic, but you have to start somewhere. -->

    <constant name="activeRegionXSize" value="lArTPCXSize - 4.0" />
    <constant name="activeRegionYSize" value="(lArTPCYSize - numberPtfeSheets*ptfeThickness) / numberActiveRegions" />
    <constant name="activeRegionZSize" value="lArTPCZSize - 4.0" />
    
    <!-- 8-May-2020 WGS: We're going to place active LAr regions separated by the PTFE 
    sheets in using a loop. -->
    <variable name="activeRegionIndex" value="0" />
    <variable name="ptfeIndex" value="0" />
    
    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: How big is a SIPM? I don't know. Make a guess. -->
    <constant name="sipmThickness" value="0.1" />
    <constant name="sipmXSize" value="1.0" />
    <constant name="sipmYSize" value="1.0" />
    <constant name="sipmZSize" value="sipmThickness" />

    <!-- ************** Scintillator walls section **************

    "Outer" and "inner" refer to the two main boxes of scintillator in the detector. 
    Think of each box as a pair of x-walls, y-walls, and z-walls. Assume that 
    opposite walls (e.g., in the plus and minus x-directions) are symmetric;
    all we need to do is define the walls one side and mirror them on the other side 
    of the box (see the <structure> section).
    
    However, the z-walls and the y-walls are _not_ the same, though they may look
    like they have the same dimensions from a distance. Assuming that all the
    scintillator strips will fit together, the lengths of the z-wall and y-wall strips
    are slightly different. 
    -->
    
    <constant name="outerVolumeXSize" value="200" />
    <constant name="outerVolumeYSize" value="350" />
    <constant name="outerVolumeZSize" value="200" />

    <!-- 5-May-2020 WGS: The sole reason I've defined the scintillator 
    width and thickness with these values is that they fit exactly in the crude
    diagram I made of the detector. In the actual GRAMs detector they'll 
    almost certainly be different. 
    -->
    <constant name="scintillatorThickness" value="1.0" />
    <constant name="scintillatorWidth"     value="2.0" />
    
    <constant name="lengthOuterZwallXstrips" value="outerVolumeXSize" />
    <constant name="lengthOuterZwallYstrips" value="outerVolumeYSize" />
    <constant name="lengthOuterYwallXstrips" value="(outerVolumeXSize - 4*scintillatorThickness)" />
    <constant name="lengthOuterYwallZstrips" value="(outerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness)" />
    <constant name="lengthOuterXwallZstrips" value="(outerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness)" />
    <constant name="lengthOuterXwallYstrips" value="outerVolumeYSize" />
    
    <constant name="numberOuterZwallXstrips" value="outerVolumeYSize / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberOuterZwallYstrips" value="outerVolumeXSize / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberOuterYwallXstrips" value="(outerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberOuterYwallZstrips" value="(outerVolumeXSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberOuterXwallZstrips" value="(outerVolumeYSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberOuterXwallYstrips" value="(outerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />

    <!-- 7-May-2020 WGS: Define "walls" in which to place the scintillator strips. This extra
    layer of geometry will make things easier in the long run; e.g., for placing the strips
    within a mechanical frame. -->

    <constant name="outerZwallXSize" value="outerVolumeXSize" />
    <constant name="outerZwallYSize" value="outerVolumeYSize" />
    <constant name="outerZwallZSize" value="2*scintillatorThickness" />

    <constant name="outerYwallXSize" value="outerVolumeXSize - 4*scintillatorThickness" />
    <constant name="outerYwallYSize" value="2*scintillatorThickness" />
    <constant name="outerYwallZSize" value="outerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness" />

    <constant name="outerXwallXSize" value="2*scintillatorThickness" />
    <constant name="outerXwallYSize" value="outerVolumeYSize" />
    <constant name="outerXwallZSize" value="outerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness" />

    <!-- 7-May-2020 WGS: Create variables for loop statements
    when we place the scintillator strips in the walls; see the <structure> section. -->
    
    <variable name="indexOuterZwallXstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexOuterZwallYstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexOuterYwallXstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexOuterYwallZstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexOuterXwallZstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexOuterXwallYstrips" value="0" />


    <constant name="innerVolumeXSize" value="30" />
    <constant name="innerVolumeYSize" value="150" />
    <constant name="innerVolumeZSize" value="30" />

    <constant name="lengthInnerZwallXstrips" value="innerVolumeXSize" />
    <constant name="lengthInnerZwallYstrips" value="innerVolumeYSize" />
    <constant name="lengthInnerYwallXstrips" value="(innerVolumeXSize - 4*scintillatorThickness)" />
    <constant name="lengthInnerYwallZstrips" value="(innerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness)" />
    <constant name="lengthInnerXwallZstrips" value="(innerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness)" />
    <constant name="lengthInnerXwallYstrips" value="innerVolumeYSize" />
    
    <constant name="numberInnerZwallXstrips" value="innerVolumeYSize / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberInnerZwallYstrips" value="innerVolumeXSize / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberInnerYwallXstrips" value="(innerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberInnerYwallZstrips" value="(innerVolumeXSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberInnerXwallZstrips" value="(innerVolumeYSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
    <constant name="numberInnerXwallYstrips" value="(innerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness) / scintillatorWidth" />
 
    <!-- 7-May-2020 WGS: Define "walls" in which to place the scintillator strips. This extra
    layer of geometry will make things easier in the long run; e.g., for placing the strips
    within a mechanical frame. -->

    <constant name="InnerZwallXSize" value="innerVolumeXSize" />
    <constant name="InnerZwallYSize" value="innerVolumeYSize" />
    <constant name="InnerZwallZSize" value="2*scintillatorThickness" />

    <constant name="InnerYwallXSize" value="innerVolumeXSize - 4*scintillatorThickness" />
    <constant name="InnerYwallYSize" value="2*scintillatorThickness" />
    <constant name="InnerYwallZSize" value="innerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness" />

    <constant name="InnerXwallXSize" value="2*scintillatorThickness" />
    <constant name="InnerXwallYSize" value="innerVolumeYSize" />
    <constant name="InnerXwallZSize" value="innerVolumeZSize - 4*scintillatorThickness" />

    <!-- 7-May-2020 WGS: Create variables for loop statements
    when we place the scintillator strips in the walls; see the <structure> section. -->

    <variable name="indexInnerZwallXstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexInnerZwallYstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexInnerYwallXstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexInnerYwallZstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexInnerXwallZstrips" value="0" />
    <variable name="indexInnerXwallYstrips" value="0" />
    
    <!-- 8-May-2020 WGS: The above walls are defined for the positive axes (x,y,z)>0.
    Assume the negative-axis walls are the mirror images of the positive ones,
    and can be defined in terms of a simple rotations. -->
    <rotation name="rPlus180AboutX" unit="deg" x="180" y="0"    z="0"  />
    <rotation name="rPlus180AboutY" unit="deg" x="0"   y="180"  z="0"  />
    <rotation name="rPlus180AboutZ" unit="deg" x="0"   y="0"    z="180"/>

    <!-- 10-May-2020 WGS: This is the offset of the inner detector from the center of
    of the outer detector. According to the diagram in arXiv:1901.03430v3, this is
    1.5m. We have to adjust a bit to make this the offset of the center of the 
    inner detector from the center of the outer detector. -->
    <constant name="innerDetectorOffsetInOuter" value ="(outerVolumeZSize - innerVolumeZSize)/2 - 150" />

    <!-- 10-May-2020 WGS: This is the offset of the outer detector from the center of
    of the world volume. This is tricky, because (to follow the LArSoft convention,
    at least partly) the Anode wires (the plane of x-wires in this tentative geometry)
    defines the z=0 axis. -->
    
    <!-- 15-May-2020 WGS: It took me 5 days to realize that, with z=0 set to the x-wires,
    all of the TPC active region have z<0. The purpose of LArSoft's definition of having
    the induction plane be at an axis=0 is to avoid negative numbers! Leave this
    for now, and let the collaboration decide an appropriate coordinate system. -->
    <constant name="outerDetectorOffsetInWorld" value ="-(lArTPCZSize/2) + (wirePlaneThickness/2) - innerDetectorOffsetInOuter" />

